# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dotenv-config
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] A **configuration file**, also known as **config file**, is a file that stores data used to configure a software system such as an application, a server or an operating system.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Some applications provide a tool to create, modify, and verify the syntax of their configuration files – sometimes via graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] For context, system administrators may be expected to create and modify text config files via a text editor.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] For server processes and operating-system settings, there is often no standard tool, but operating systems may provide graphical interfaces such as YaST or debconf.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Some computer programs only read their configuration files at startup.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Others periodically check the configuration files for changes.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Users can instruct some programs to re-read the configuration files and apply the changes to the current process, or indeed to read arbitrary files as a configuration file.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] There are no definitive standards or strong conventions.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] In general, a config file can have any format.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] The format that applies to a particular system is determined by the design of that system.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Often, a standardized format is used since it allows for using tools designed for the format even if not designed for the consuming system.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] In particular, general-purpose serialization formats, such as JSON, XML, and YAML, are often used in open-source and platform-neutral software.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] The specifications for these formats are generally publicly available to support wide-spread use.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] The following table compares notable formats used for configuration data.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] The *syntax typing* column indicates whether the syntax supports data types.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] A format has syntax-typing if a value's type is specified by syntax – e.g.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] `true` is a Boolean while `"true"` is a string.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] A format does not have syntax-typing if a value's type is based on semantics – e.g.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] `true` and `"true"` are both Boolean if the parser expects a Boolean.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Opinions on the value of syntax-typing vary.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] The following are examples of config files organized by the operating systems on which they are commonly used.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Many different file formats are used on Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Even so, there is a strong tradition of using human-editable, plain text formats including simple key–value pair.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Filename extensions of `.cnf`, `.conf`, `.cfg`, `.cf` or `.ini` are often used.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Many formats allow comments, in which case, individual settings can be disabled by prepending with the comment character.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Often the default configuration files contain extensive internal documentation in the form of comments and man files are also typically used to document the format and options available.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] System-wide software often uses configuration files stored in `/etc`, while user applications often use a "dotfile" – a file or directory in the home directory prefixed with a period, which in Unix hides the file or directory from casual listing.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Since this causes pollution, newer user applications generally make their own folder in the `.config` directory, a standardized subdirectory of the home directory.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Similar to config files, a run command (rc) shell script can configure a shell session.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Often, such scripts are named with an `rc` suffix after the consuming program's name such as `.xinitrc`, `.vimrc`, `.bashrc`, `xsane.rc`.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] By contrast, IBM's AIX uses an Object Data Manager (ODM) database to store much of its system settings.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] MS-DOS primarily relied on the `CONFIG.SYS` config file, a plain text file with simple key–value pairs (e.g.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] MS-DOS 6 introduced the INI-file format.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Similar to an rc file, the batch file named `AUTOEXEC.BAT` ran commands on startup.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Both these files were retained up to Windows 98SE, which still ran on top of MS-DOS.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] DOS applications used a wide variety of individual configuration files, most of them binary, proprietary and undocumented - and there were no common conventions or formats.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Early Windows operating systems heavily utilized plain-text INI files which served as the primary mechanism to configure the operating system and applications.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] The APIs to read and write from these still exist in Windows, but after 1993, Microsoft began to steer developers away from using INI files and toward storing settings in the registry, a hierarchical database to store configuration settings, which was introduced with Windows NT.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Later systems use XML and other formats instead of the registry.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] The Property List is the standard configuration file format in macOS (as well as in iOS, NeXTSTEP, GNUstep and Cocoa applications).
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] It uses the filename extension `.plist`.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] IBM's OS/2 uses a binary format, also with a .INI suffix, but this differs from the Windows versions.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] It contains a list of lists of untyped key–value pairs.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Two files control system-wide settings: OS2.INI and OS2SYS.INI.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] Application developers can choose whether to use them or to create a specific file for their applications.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] HarmonyOS and OpenHarmony-based operating systems use JSON config files, named `config.json`.
[src:dotenv-config/configuration-file] The platform IDE, DevEco Studio, provides methods for editing `config.json`.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] An **environment variable** is a user-definable value that can affect the way running processes will behave on a computer.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are part of the environment in which a process runs.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] For example, a running process can query the value of the TEMP environment variable to discover a suitable location to store temporary files, or the HOME or USERPROFILE variable to find the directory structure owned by the user running the process.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] They were introduced in their modern form in 1979 with Version 7 Unix, so are included in all Unix operating system flavors and variants from that point onward including Linux and macOS.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] From PC DOS 2.0 in 1982, all succeeding Microsoft operating systems, including Microsoft Windows, and OS/2 also have included them as a feature, although with somewhat different syntax, usage and standard variable names.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In all Unix and Unix-like systems, as well as on Windows, each process has its own separate set of environment variables.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] By default, when a process is created, it inherits a duplicate run-time environment of its parent process, except for explicit changes made by the parent when it creates the child.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] At the API level, these changes must be done between running `fork` and `exec`.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] Alternatively, from command shells such as bash, a user can change environment variables for a particular command invocation by indirectly invoking it via `env` or using the `ENVIRONMENT_VARIABLE=VALUE <command>` notation.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] A running program can access the values of environment variables for configuration purposes.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] Shell scripts and batch files use environment variables to communicate data and preferences to child processes.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] They can also be used to store temporary values for reference later in a shell script.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] However, in Unix, non-exported variables are preferred for this as they do not leak outside the process.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, an environment variable that is changed in a script or compiled program will only affect that process and possibly child processes.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The parent process and any unrelated processes will not be affected.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] Similarly, changing or removing a variable's value inside a DOS or Windows batch file will change the variable for the duration of `COMMAND.COM`or `CMD.EXE`'s existence, respectively.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In Unix, the environment variables are normally initialized during system startup by the system init startup scripts, and hence inherited by all other processes in the system.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] Users can, and often do, augment them in the profile script for the command shell they are using.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In Microsoft Windows, each environment variable's default value is stored in the Windows Registry or set in the `AUTOEXEC.BAT` file.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] On Unix, a setuid program is given an environment chosen by its caller, but it runs with different authority from its caller.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The dynamic linker will usually load code from locations specified by the environment variables `$LD_LIBRARY_PATH` and `$LD_PRELOAD` and run it with the process's authority.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] If a setuid program did this, it would be insecure, because its caller could get it to run arbitrary code and hence misuse its authority.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] For this reason, libc unsets these environment variables at startup in a setuid process. setuid programs usually unset unknown environment variables and check others or set them to reasonable values.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In general, the collection of environment variables function as an associative array where both the keys and values are strings.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The interpretation of characters in either string differs among systems.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] When data structures such as lists need to be represented, it is common to use a colon (common on Unix and Unix-like) or semicolon-delineated (common on Windows and DOS) list.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The variables can be used both in scripts and on the command line.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] They are usually referenced by putting special symbols in front of or around the variable name.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] By convention, names of environment variables are normally expressed in all capital letters.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] This helps keep environment variables distinctly different from other variables and identifiers used in programming codes.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] Nevertheless, note that case sensitivity in environment variable names differs between operating systems.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] That is, Unix-like operating systems are case-sensitive with respect to environment variable names, while DOS, OS/2, and Windows are not case-sensitive.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In most Unix and Unix-like command-line shells, an environment variable's value is retrieved by placing a `$` sign before the variable's name.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] If necessary, the name can also be surrounded by braces.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the names of environment variables are case-sensitive.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The command **`env`** displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The command **`printenv`** can also be used to print a single variable by giving that variable name as the sole argument to the command.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters such as `COMMAND.COM` and `CMD.EXE`, an environment variable is retrieved by placing a `%` sign before and after it.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows command-line interpreters as well as their API, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The environment variable named `HOMEDRIVE` contains the drive letter (plus its trailing `:` colon) of the user's home directory, whilst `HOMEPATH` contains the full path of the user's home directory within that drive.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The command **`SET`** (with no arguments) displays all environment variables and their values.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In Windows NT and later `set` can also be used to print all variables whose name begins with a given prefix by giving the prefix as the sole argument to the command.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In PowerShell, upper or lower case is not distinguished for environment variable names.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The commands `env` and `set` can be used to set environment variables and are often incorporated directly into the shell.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The following commands can also be used, but are often dependent on a certain shell.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] A few simple principles govern how environment variables achieve their effect.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] Environment variables are local to the process in which they were set.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] If two shell processes are spawned and the value of an environment variable is changed in one, that change will not be seen by the other.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] When a child process is created, it inherits all the environment variables and their values from the parent process.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] Usually, when a program calls another program, it first creates a child process by forking, then the child adjusts the environment as needed and lastly the child replaces itself with the program to be called.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] This procedure gives the calling program control over the environment of the called program.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In Unix shells, variables may be assigned without the **`export`** keyword.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] Variables defined in this way are displayed by the **`set`** command, but are *not* true environment variables, as they are stored only by the shell and are unknown to all other processes.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The `printenv` command will not display them, and child processes do not inherit them.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The persistence of an environment variable can be session-wide or system-wide.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] The **`SET`** command without any arguments displays all environment variables along with their values; **`SET " "`**, zero or more spaces, will include internal variables too.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In `CMD.EXE`, it is possible to assign local variables that will not be global using the **`SETLOCAL`** command and **`ENDLOCAL`** to restore the environment.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p01] In PHP the `putenv()` function should be used.
