[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] The command processors in DOS and Windows also support pseudo-environment variables.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] These are values that are fetched like environment variables, but are not truly stored in the environment but computed when requested.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] Besides true environment variables, which are statically stored in the environment until changed or deleted, a number of pseudo-environment variables exist for batch processing.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] In batchjobs, they can be retrieved just like environment variables, but are not actually stored in the environment.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] The returned values represent the status of the system in the moment these variables are queried; that is, reading them multiple times in a row may return different values even within the same command; querying them has no direct effect on the system.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] Since they are not stored in the environment, they are not listed by SET and do not exist for external programs to retrieve.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] If a true environment variable of the same name is defined, it takes precedence over the corresponding variable until the environment variable is deleted again.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] While almost all such variables are prefixed with an underscore ("`_`") by 4DOS etc. by convention (f.e.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] `%_SECOND%`), they are not under DR-DOS `COMMAND.COM` (f.e.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] In addition, 4DOS, 4OS2, 4NT, and Take Command also support so called *variable functions*, including user-definable ones.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] They work just like *internal variables*, but can take optional parameters (f.e.
[src:dotenv-config/environment-variable-p02] `%@EVAL[]%`) and may even change the system status depending on their function.
