[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] The **`JSON`** namespace object contains static methods for parsing values from and converting values to JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Unlike most global objects, `JSON` is not a constructor.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] You cannot use it with the `new` operator or invoke the `JSON` object as a function.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] All properties and methods of `JSON` are static (just like the `Math` object).
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] JSON is a syntax for serializing objects, arrays, numbers, strings, booleans, and `null`.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] It is based upon JavaScript syntax, but is distinct from JavaScript: most of JavaScript is *not* JSON.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Property names must be double-quoted strings; trailing commas are forbidden.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] A decimal point must be followed by at least one digit.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Any JSON text is a valid JavaScript expression, but only after the JSON superset revision.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Before the revision, U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR are allowed in string literals and property keys in JSON; but the same use in JavaScript string literals is a `SyntaxError`.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Other differences include allowing only double-quoted strings and no support for `undefined` or comments.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] For those who wish to use a more human-friendly configuration format based on JSON, there is JSON5, used by the Babel compiler, and the more commonly used YAML.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] The same text may represent different values in JavaScript object literals vs.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] For more information, see Object literal syntax vs.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Insignificant whitespace may be present anywhere except within a `JSONNumber` (numbers must contain no whitespace) or `JSONString` (where it is interpreted as the corresponding character in the string, or would cause an error).
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] The tab (U+0009), carriage return (U+000D), line feed (U+000A), and space (U+0020) characters are the only valid whitespace characters.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"JSON"`.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Tests whether a value is an object returned by `JSON.rawJSON()`.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Parse a piece of string text as JSON, optionally transforming the produced value and its properties, and return the value.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Creates a "raw JSON" object containing a piece of JSON text.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] When serialized to JSON, the raw JSON object is treated as if it is already a piece of JSON.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Return a JSON string corresponding to the specified value, optionally including only certain properties or replacing property values in a user-defined manner.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] JSON can contain number literals of arbitrary precision.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] However, it is not possible to represent all JSON numbers exactly in JavaScript, because JavaScript uses floating point representation which has a fixed precision.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] This means there is no JavaScript number that corresponds precisely to the `12345678901234567890` JSON number.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] You want to serialize it and then parse to the same exact number.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] There are, in general, two ways to ensure that numbers are losslessly converted to JSON and parsed back: one involves a JSON number, another involves a JSON string.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] JSON is a *communication format*, so if you use JSON, you are likely communicating with another system (HTTP request, storing in database, etc.).
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] The best solution to choose depends on the recipient system.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] If the recipient system does not have same JSON-handling capabilities as JavaScript, and does not support high precision numbers, you may want to serialize the number as a string, and then handle it as a string on the recipient side.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] This is also the only option in older JavaScript.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] To specify how custom data types (including `BigInt`) should be serialized to JSON, either add a `toJSON` method to your data type, or use the `replacer` function of `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] In either case, the JSON text will look like `{"gross_gdp":"12345678901234567890"}`, where the value is a string, not a number.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] Then, on the recipient side, you can parse the JSON and handle the string.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] If the recipient of this message natively supports high precision numbers (such as Python integers), passing numbers as JSON numbers is obviously better, because they can directly parse to the high precision type instead of parsing a string from JSON, and then parsing a number from the string.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] In JavaScript, you can serialize arbitrary data types to JSON numbers without producing a number value first (resulting in loss of precision) by using `JSON.rawJSON()` to precisely specify what the JSON source text should be.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] The text passed to `JSON.rawJSON` is treated as if it is already a piece of JSON, so it won't be serialized again as a string.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] This JSON can then be parsed by the recipient without any extra processing, provided that the recipient system does not have the same precision limitations as JavaScript.
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] When parsing JSON containing high-precision numbers in JavaScript, take extra care because when `JSON.parse()` invokes the `reviver` function, the value you receive is already parsed (and has lost precision).
[src:dotenv-config/global-objects-json] You can use the `context.source` parameter of the `JSON.parse()` `reviver` function to re-parse the number yourself.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] A module interface expresses the elements that are provided and required by the module.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] The elements defined in the interface are detectable by other modules.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] The implementation contains the working code that corresponds to the elements declared in the interface.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Modular programming, in the form of subsystems (particularly for I/O) and software libraries, dates to early software systems, where it was used for code reuse.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Modular programming per se, with a goal of modularity, developed in the late 1960s and 1970s, as a larger-scale analog of the concept of structured programming (1960s).
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] The term "modular programming" dates at least to the National Symposium on Modular Programming, organized at the Information and Systems Institute in July 1968 by Larry Constantine; other key concepts were information hiding (1972) and separation of concerns (SoC, 1974).
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Modules were not included in the original specification for ALGOL 68 (1968), but were included as extensions in early implementations, ALGOL 68-R (1970) and ALGOL 68C (1970), and later formalized.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] One of the first languages designed from the start for modular programming was the short-lived Modula (1975), by Niklaus Wirth.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Another early modular language was Mesa (1970s), by Xerox PARC, and Wirth drew on Mesa as well as the original Modula in its successor, Modula-2 (1978), which influenced later languages, particularly through its successor, Modula-3 (1980s).
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Modula's use of dot-qualified names, like `M.a` to refer to object `a` from module `M`, coincides with notation to access a field of a record (and similarly for attributes or methods of objects), and is now widespread, seen in C++, C#, Dart, Go, Java, OCaml, and Python, among others.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Modular programming became widespread from the 1980s: the original Pascal language (1970) did not include modules, but later versions, notably UCSD Pascal (1978) and Turbo Pascal (1983) included them in the form of "units", as did the Pascal-influenced Ada (1980).
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] The Extended Pascal ISO 10206:1990 standard kept closer to Modula2 in its modular support.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Standard ML (1984) has one of the most complete module systems, including functors (parameterized modules) to map between modules.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] In the 1980s and 1990s, modular programming was overshadowed by and often conflated with object-oriented programming, particularly due to the popularity of C++ and Java.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] For example, the C family of languages had support for objects and classes in C++ (originally C with Classes, 1980) and Objective-C (1983), only supporting modules 30 years or more later.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Java (1995) supports modules in the form of packages, though the primary unit of code organization is a class.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] However, Python (1991) prominently used both modules and objects from the start, using modules as the primary unit of code organization and "packages" as a larger-scale unit.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Perl 5 (1994) also includes support for both modules and objects, with a vast array of modules being available from CPAN (1993).
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] OCaml (1996) followed ML by supporting modules and functors.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Modular programming is now widespread, and found in virtually all major languages developed since the 1990s.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] The relative importance of modules varies between languages, and in class-based object-oriented languages there is still overlap and confusion with classes as a unit of organization and encapsulation, but these are both well-established as distinct concepts.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] The term *assembly* (as in .NET languages like C#, F#, or Visual Basic) or *package* (as in Dart, Go, or Java) is sometimes used instead of *module*.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] In other implementations, these are distinct concepts; in Python a package is a set of modules, while in Java 9 the introduction of the Java Platform Module System, in which a new module concept, involving a set of packages with enhanced access control, was implemented.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] In Java, the term *package* is used for the module concept in the Java language specification.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] The *module*, a kind of set of a package, was introduced in Java 9.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] In some Pascal dialects, the term *unit* is used for the module concept.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] A component is a similar concept, but typically refers to a higher level; a component is a piece of a whole system, while a module is a piece of an individual program.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] The scale of the term "module" varies significantly between languages; in Python it is very small-scale and each file is a module, while in Java 9 it is large-scale, where a module is a set of packages, which are in turn sets of files.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Conspicuous examples of languages that lack support for modules are C, and in their original forms, C++ and Pascal.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] C and C++ do, however, allow separate compilation and declarative interfaces to be specified using header files which is commonly considered modularization.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Modules were added to Objective-C in iOS 7 (2013), and to C++ with C++20.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Pascal was superseded by Modula and Oberon, which included modules from the start, and various derivatives that included modules.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] JavaScript has had native modules since ECMAScript 2015.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] C++ modules have allowed backwards compatibility with headers (with "header units").
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Dialects of C allow for modules, for example Clang supports modules for the C language, though the syntax and semantics of Clang C modules differ from C++ modules.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Modular programming can be performed even where the programming language lacks explicit syntactic features to support named modules, like, for example, in C.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] This is done by using existing language features, together with, for example, coding conventions, programming idioms and the physical code structure.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] IBM i also uses modules when programming in the Integrated Language Environment (ILE).
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] With modular programming, concerns are separated such that modules perform logically discrete functions, interacting through well-defined interfaces.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Often modules form a directed acyclic graph (DAG); in this case a cyclic dependency between modules is seen as indicating that these should be a single module.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] In the case where modules do form a DAG they can be arranged as a hierarchy, where the lowest-level modules are independent, depending on no other modules, and higher-level modules depend on lower-level ones.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] A particular program or library is a top-level module of its own hierarchy, but can in turn be seen as a lower-level module of a higher-level program, library, or system.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] When creating a modular system, instead of creating a monolithic application (where the smallest component is the whole), several smaller modules are written separately so when they are composed together, they construct the executable application program.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Typically, these are also compiled separately, via separate compilation, and then linked by a linker.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] A just-in-time compiler may perform some of this construction "on-the-fly" at run time.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] These independent functions are commonly classified as either program control functions or specific task functions.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Program control functions are designed to work for one program.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Specific task functions are closely prepared to be applicable for various programs.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] This makes modular designed systems, if built correctly, far more reusable than a traditional monolithic design, since all (or many) of these modules may then be reused (without change) in other projects.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] This also facilitates the "breaking down" of projects into several smaller projects.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] Theoretically, a modularized software project will be more easily assembled by large teams, since no team members are creating the whole system, or even need to know about the system as a whole.
[src:dotenv-config/modular-programming] They can focus just on the assigned smaller task.
[src:dotenv-config/motdotla-dotenv] Dotenv is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a `.env` file into `process.env`.
[src:dotenv-config/motdotla-dotenv] Storing configuration in the environment separate from code is based on The Twelve-Factor App methodology.
