[src:dotenv-config/motdotla-dotenv] Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
[src:dotenv-config/motdotla-dotenv] The engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use.
[src:dotenv-config/motdotla-dotenv] It accepts a target, a source, and options.
[src:dotenv-config/motdotla-dotenv] This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
[src:dotenv-config/motdotla-dotenv] Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
[src:dotenv-config/motdotla-dotenv] Override any environment variables that have already been set.
[src:dotenv-config/motdotla-dotenv] Projects that expand it often use the keyword "dotenv" on npm.
[src:dotenv-config/twelve-factor-app-methodology] The **Twelve-Factor App methodology** is a methodology for building software-as-a-service applications.
[src:dotenv-config/twelve-factor-app-methodology] These best practices are designed to enable applications to be built with portability and resilience when deployed to the web.
[src:dotenv-config/twelve-factor-app-methodology] The methodology was drafted by developers at Heroku, a platform-as-a-service company, and was first presented by Adam Wiggins circa 2011.
[src:dotenv-config/twelve-factor-app-methodology] An Nginx architect argued that the relevance of the Twelve-Factor app concept is somewhat specific to Heroku, while introducing their own (Nginx's) proposed architecture for microservices.
[src:dotenv-config/twelve-factor-app-methodology] The twelve factors are however cited as a baseline from which to adapt or extend.
[src:dotenv-config/type-conversion] Type conversion (or typecasting) means transfer of data from one data type to another.
[src:dotenv-config/type-conversion] *Implicit conversion* happens when the compiler (for compiled languages) or runtime (for script languages like JavaScript) automatically converts data types.
[src:dotenv-config/type-conversion] The source code can also *explicitly* require a conversion to take place.
[src:dotenv-config/type-conversion] For example, given the expression `"foo" + 1`, the Number `1` is implicitly converted into a String and the expression returns `"foo1"`.
[src:dotenv-config/type-conversion] Given the instruction `Number("0x11")`, the string `"0x11"` is explicitly converted to the number `17`.
